## Key Concepts Understood

- A router connects different networks/subnets using IP addresses.
- A switch connects local wired devices using MAC addresses.
- A managed switch supports features such as VLANs, port monitoring, and port control.
- A VLAN separates groups of connected devices into logical networks/broadcast domains.
- An access point connects wireless devices to a wired network.
- A patch panel organizes permanent Ethernet cable runs; a switch forwards traffic.
- PoE allows Ethernet cabling to carry both data and electrical power.
- An ONT converts fibre-optic service into Ethernet/network connections.
- A subnet mask helps a device decide whether traffic is local or must go to the default gateway.
- A default gateway is the router used to reach other networks or the internet.
- APIPA addresses usually indicate that DHCP is not reachable.
- WISP provides internet wirelessly from a ground-based provider antenna.
- LAN, WAN, PAN, MAN, SAN, and WLAN describe different network scopes or purposes.
- Network tools are used for cable creation, cable testing, port testing, Wi-Fi analysis, cable tracing, and traffic capture.

